  "prompt": "What kind of genetic tests are now available to the consumer?",
  "response": "There are several types of genetic tests available to consumers:\n\n1. Ancestry and Ethnicity Tests\n- 23andMe\n- AncestryDNA\n- MyHeritage DNA\n\n2. Health and Disease Risk Tests\n- Genetic predisposition to certain conditions\n- Carrier screening for inherited diseases\n- Pharmacogenomics (drug response)\n\n3. Wellness and Traits Tests\n- Nutritional predispositions\n- Fitness and exercise genetics\n- Skin and physical characteristics\n\n4. Paternity and Relationship Testing\n- Determining biological relationships\n- Parentage verification\n\n5. Cancer Risk Tests\n- BRCA1/BRCA2 mutations\n- Genetic markers for hereditary cancers\n\n6. Rare Disease Screening\n- Diagnostic tests for specific genetic disorders\n- Comprehensive genome sequencing\n\n7. Nutrigenomics\n- Personalized nutrition recommendations\n- Genetic diet and metabolism insights\n\n8. Whole Genome Sequencing\n- Most comprehensive genetic analysis\n- Detailed genetic information\n\nMost consumer tests are done through saliva or cheek swab samples, with results typically provided online through secure platforms. Prices range from $50 to several hundred dollars depending on the complexity of the test.",
